that to today for what MCP is good for and what it's not. The first one is whether it's the right

00:12:03.580 --> 00:12:07.659
tool for the job. Should you use MCP server, should you use a command line utility, or should

00:12:07.659 --> 00:12:15.780
you use a skill? Now, remember, the agent skills standard came after MCP, so it did not exist at

00:12:15.780 --> 00:12:23.940
the time. Skills are great. If you can describe everything you want to do with tools that your

00:12:23.940 --> 00:12:29.900
agent already has, like Bash or the web fetch or anything like that, then a skill is all you need.

00:12:29.900 --> 00:12:35.179
You just tell it how to use things it already knows how to do. Otherwise, a skill is really a

00:12:35.179 --> 00:12:42.020
complement, and I think a very productive pattern is to have a skill that goes with your CLI or with

00:12:42.020 --> 00:12:46.260
your MCP server. Here are the tools, and here's how you use them. Here's how you compose them

00:12:46.260 --> 00:12:52.539
together. So the choice you're actually making is really between MCP and skill or CLI and skill.

