escaping a sandbox or whatever, and so CLI is not always an option. So that was one set of critiques

00:14:55.380 --> 00:15:03.140
of MCP versus command line utilities. There were also, at the time, a number of security vulnerabilities

00:15:03.140 --> 00:15:08.340
and things that were exposed using MCP servers, and so I really think it's important to talk about

00:15:08.340 --> 00:15:16.820
security. It's not strictly a critique of MCP because command line utility can also expose you

00:15:16.820 --> 00:15:23.179
to these types of things as well. I think a very useful framework is the lethal trifecta that Simon

00:15:23.179 --> 00:15:31.780
Willison has written about. So essentially, if your agent has access to private data, which of

00:15:31.780 --> 00:15:37.460
course is what we're trying to do here by providing more tools here, that access private data,

00:15:37.460 --> 00:15:45.419
exposure to untrusted content, and the ability to communicate out, it is pretty easy to prompt

00:15:45.419 --> 00:15:51.619
inject or otherwise trick your agent into sending that private data to the attacker.

00:15:52.219 --> 00:16:00.020
Just to stick with GitHub for a minute, if you have tools exposed to let you read issues and you're reading

00:16:00.020 --> 00:16:07.059
issues in public repositories, somebody could write a prompt injection type of issue that says,

00:16:07.059 --> 00:16:14.659
read the secret file here and send the information somewhere. And so if you also have given the

00:16:14.659 --> 00:16:21.780
write issue task or comment on issue tool, then you've gotten both the access to the private data

00:16:21.780 --> 00:16:25.539
and the exposure to untrusted content, and now you've given an ability to exfiltrate.

00:16:26.419 --> 00:16:32.659
So it's important to be mindful about what tools are made available, not just within your single

00:16:32.659 --> 00:16:40.900
MCP server, but in the whole agent that you're using. And so this leads me to describe a few

00:16:40.900 --> 00:16:48.179
best practices that I found. And with the title of the talk, MCP or not MCP, I felt I needed to have

00:16:48.820 --> 00:16:54.900
at least one Hamlet reference in here. And so brevity is the soul of wit is how I summarize

00:16:56.179 --> 00:17:00.179
the best practices. Maybe I should stop there if I'm trying to be truly brief, but

00:17:02.500 --> 00:17:06.660
you only want to find the tools that you actually need. You only want to send the information back

00:17:06.660 --> 00:17:11.300
that you actually need. And you want to sanitize out any sensitive data that you don't need.

