having just the tools that we care about referenced in is really important.

00:21:17.459 --> 00:21:22.260
The other thing, though, is about security. So under the ticket endpoints, there's this great

00:21:22.260 --> 00:21:27.380
one where I can bulk delete tickets. And with my API key on Zendesk, I could do that,

00:21:28.420 --> 00:21:35.140
but I do not want to give that to my agent. So by being selective about what tools we give,

00:21:36.180 --> 00:21:43.459
we can limit the impact of what our agent could do and also make it more efficient. So

00:21:43.859 --> 00:21:51.780
many of the MCP servers that I use in production now intentionally only expose read-only tools,

00:21:52.420 --> 00:21:56.900
because I don't know where they're going to be composed into other agents, but I want to make

00:21:56.900 --> 00:22:04.819
sure that I just need to get the facts out. I don't need to open myself up to any sort of

00:22:05.540 --> 00:22:11.459
exposure for lethal trifecta attacks there. I've cut off the ability to exfiltrate with this one.

00:22:12.260 --> 00:22:20.020
All right. So the next thing to do is to make our responses concise. So this is a much sanitized

00:22:20.020 --> 00:22:27.939
version of the next tool call that I have that I use a lot, which is to list the ticket comments.

00:22:27.939 --> 00:22:33.699
This comes back in a separate resource in the API, and it's all of the back and forth discussions of

00:22:35.219 --> 00:22:39.780
what if you do this? I did this, and here's what the log is. Okay, what about this? All the

00:22:39.780 --> 00:22:49.140
discussion. And the actual REST API is very verbose here. Some of it is information that's

00:22:49.140 --> 00:22:55.540
probably useful for rendering the web page, the web app for Zendesk, and some of it is just

00:22:56.819 --> 00:23:04.180
analytics and stuff that's not helpful at all. So here there's actually two or maybe three copies

00:23:04.180 --> 00:23:08.660
of the body of the comments. There's a plain text one that I'm keeping,

00:23:08.660 --> 00:23:13.459
but I'm removing the HTML body and whatever the other body is, too. So there's one that's got

00:23:13.459 --> 00:23:18.180
rich formatting on it. I definitely don't need two copies of it, let alone three.

00:23:20.099 --> 00:23:30.180
Metadata is interesting. It will include things like the user agent string and IP and location

00:23:30.180 --> 00:23:38.260
of the browser of the person when they logged into the portal to leave a comment on the issue,

00:23:39.219 --> 00:23:43.780
which is probably useful for somebody but is not useful for Claude in trying to help me understand

00:23:44.660 --> 00:23:51.380
the substance of it. Likewise with attachments, I need to know that there's an attachment. The

00:23:51.380 --> 00:23:55.619
attachment could be the logs that I want. I have a separate tool for being able to process

00:23:56.180 --> 00:24:02.020
the attachments, but I don't need the thumbnail of the image or whatever. Let's all just junk.

00:24:03.939 --> 00:24:08.420
And if you forget to do this, if you forget to clean your responses, Claude will probably let

00:24:08.420 --> 00:24:14.739
you know. Your agent will let you know. The reason why I ended up noticing I need to do this was I

00:24:14.739 --> 00:24:21.939
would make a tool call and it would come back and say large MCP tool response, like 20 kilobytes or

00:24:21.939 --> 00:24:30.500
whatever. I was like, that's insane. So by trimming this, you're helping focus your tool

00:24:30.500 --> 00:24:36.739
responses, you're helping focus your agent on the things that it actually needs. So again,

00:24:36.739 --> 00:24:43.699
we're building an API that is specific for AI agents. So anything else that's in the API response

00:24:44.660 --> 00:24:51.699
that is not useful for that, we can get rid of. As a human, I can read the JSON dictionary

00:24:52.420 --> 00:24:56.900
into memory and I can just choose not to look at the two other copies of the

00:24:57.619 --> 00:25:01.540
comment body. But the agent doesn't have that choice. It's all just tokens, right?

00:25:02.420 --> 00:25:08.420
So less context means lower cost and more likely to get the answer that you're looking for.

00:25:09.140 --> 00:25:15.859
And finally, I didn't actually do this in this particular MCP server, but it's also good to

00:25:15.859 --> 00:25:21.380
just be mindful of your data hygiene. And so if there's any personally identifying information

00:25:21.380 --> 00:25:27.380
that you're pulling in potentially and the agent doesn't need it, you can strip it out. So here's

00:25:27.380 --> 00:25:34.660
just a function that strips out the username but keeps the domain for an email. So I could still

00:25:35.540 --> 00:25:41.060
see that somebody from Posit left this comment, but the individual is not identified.

00:25:43.300 --> 00:25:50.819
So again, when you're building the MCP server, you might not know right away what agents it's

00:25:50.819 --> 00:25:56.579
going to get pulled into. I have restricted to only read-only tools, so I'm not exposing

00:25:57.219 --> 00:26:03.459
within this particular MCP server to the lethal trifecta. But if someone else is in their agent,

00:26:03.459 --> 00:26:07.459
they take this MCP and they take another one that's got the ability, maybe it doesn't expose

00:26:07.459 --> 00:26:10.660
private data, but it has the ability to write, then we're kind of back in there.

00:26:12.339 --> 00:26:19.780
But this is something that we can and must, as owners of these projects, take care of.

00:26:21.300 --> 00:26:27.140
So there's some practice basically being as concise as you can be in what tools you define

00:26:27.140 --> 00:26:31.699
and what you include in the response. If we were to host this as a local MCP server,

00:26:31.699 --> 00:26:37.939
that would still be pretty good. This would have solved the problem that I had initially,

00:26:37.939 --> 00:26:43.300
which is I couldn't authenticate with Zendesk, because I could take my API key, put it in the

00:26:43.300 --> 00:26:49.939
environment where my local MCP server is running, and it's still out of the models context.

00:26:50.900 --> 00:26:57.140
We'd be efficient with tokens. We reduced our exposure to the lethal trifecta.

00:26:57.219 --> 00:27:02.660
But it's still not as great. The distribution story is not as great, in particular because

00:27:02.660 --> 00:27:07.540
that means that anyone else that wants to use this needs to get their own API key and put it

00:27:07.540 --> 00:27:13.699
somewhere on their machine. And now we don't really like having long-lived API tokens around,

00:27:14.260 --> 00:27:19.060
particularly those that if someone got a hold of it, they could bulk delete tickets, right?

00:27:19.619 --> 00:27:26.339
So a remote server would be superior. So we need a place to deploy it. And because

00:27:26.339 --> 00:27:36.180
this is just an HTTP API, anywhere that you can host APIs would work. You can self-host it inside

00:27:36.180 --> 00:27:42.819
Docker. If you work at a company that has a platform for deploying things, you probably

00:27:42.819 --> 00:27:49.859
have a place to do this. There are platforms that are more aware of the MCP spec and all the things

00:27:49.859 --> 00:27:56.339
it can do. PositConnect is one of them. There are others that are good choices as well. If you

00:27:56.979 --> 00:28:03.219
do deploy on a platform that is aware of some of these things, you can get more out of it. And the

00:28:03.219 --> 00:28:10.260
first one that's really nice is that there is authentication built into the MCP standard.

00:28:10.979 --> 00:28:19.060
It's an OAuth 2.1 flow. So what happens is if your server supports it,

00:28:20.739 --> 00:28:27.380
I can just give you the URL. And when Cloud connects to the MCP server, it says authentication

00:28:27.380 --> 00:28:34.660
is needed. Because we're meeting the standards that is in MCP, it knows how to go

00:28:35.300 --> 00:28:39.939
register itself and then start this login flow. It kicks you out to the browser, you log in,

00:28:40.180 --> 00:28:45.619
it says authentication successful. You can close this. And that's built into the MCP standard.

00:28:45.619 --> 00:28:50.660
So you don't have to have, you can have authentication built in in a way that's

00:28:50.660 --> 00:28:56.180
only short-lived tokens. It's also possible that if your MCP server requires auth

00:28:56.900 --> 00:29:02.579
and supports API keys or API tokens, that you can put them, you can define custom headers

00:29:02.579 --> 00:29:08.020
when you configure it. And that's still, that gets you kind of like what I was describing

00:29:08.020 --> 00:29:14.739
with the local MCP. It's in the configuration for MCP. It's not in the model's, the agent's

00:29:14.739 --> 00:29:18.979
context. So it's still out of there, it still works, but it is a long-lived key that you're

00:29:18.979 --> 00:29:24.339
maintaining. Other things you can get from a platform that is designed for deploying things

00:29:24.339 --> 00:29:28.660
like this is, you know, access control. You can limit who has access to this server.

00:29:30.099 --> 00:29:35.140
We obviously care a lot more about observability and monitoring and all sorts of enterprise-y

00:29:35.140 --> 00:29:40.979
things with AI because of the potential effects of what it could do.

00:29:42.660 --> 00:29:47.780
And there's other enterprise-y things you could do. One thing that I actually used

00:29:47.780 --> 00:29:53.219
deploying this on Posit Connect is Connect supports integrations, third-party integrations.

00:29:53.780 --> 00:30:01.060
And so there's no actual API key for Zendesk where I've deployed it. It's got an OAuth app

00:30:01.060 --> 00:30:05.859
with Zendesk, and so it's a short-lived token exchange there, and then a short-lived token

00:30:05.859 --> 00:30:12.180
exchange to the users as well. So these are all things that the security teams,

00:30:12.180 --> 00:30:16.500
my security team in particular, was very interested in making sure that we were doing.

00:30:18.900 --> 00:30:22.579
If you don't have a platform that does these things for you, you can build a lot of these

00:30:22.579 --> 00:30:28.579
things into your server. I think FastMTP has tooling for authentication and authorization.

00:30:28.579 --> 00:30:31.939
It's totally doable. It's just more work for you or your agent to do.

00:30:33.540 --> 00:30:37.939
I've said this a few times, but the great thing about Remote MCP is that distribution is just

00:30:37.939 --> 00:30:46.020
this URL. You could write a CLI, and you could have the CLI develop its own key store to handle

00:30:46.020 --> 00:30:52.739
auth for you and stuff. And maybe you could get it to be more efficient with tokens and a context

00:30:52.739 --> 00:30:58.900
window, but you still have to have everybody go download and install your CLI, and when you

00:30:58.900 --> 00:31:01.540
update it, you still have to tell them to update it.

00:31:01.744 --> 00:31:05.224
have to tell them to update it.

00:31:05.224 --> 00:31:08.464
Whereas this case, I own this MCP server.

00:31:08.464 --> 00:31:09.464
I own the deployment.

00:31:09.464 --> 00:31:13.304
If I want to add another tool, or I want to take a tool away.

00:31:10.665 --> 00:31:12.665
away, I can do that.

00:31:12.665 --> 00:31:13.665
And I own that.

00:31:13.665 --> 00:31:16.145
And then whoever is just connected to this URL,

00:31:16.145 --> 00:31:19.425
they automatically get those updates.

00:31:19.425 --> 00:31:21.385
And also importantly, like I said,

00:31:21.385 --> 00:31:23.265
I want to make this available to people

00:31:23.265 --> 00:31:28.785
that aren't developers, maybe don't live in Cloud Code

00:31:28.785 --> 00:31:30.665
like me and my team do.

00:31:30.665 --> 00:31:33.105
And so this works in Cloud Desktop.

00:31:33.105 --> 00:31:35.565
It works in other AI applications

00:31:35.565 --> 00:31:39.025
that aren't code-oriented.

00:31:39.025 --> 00:31:46.385
OK, so to call back to the title, MCP, or not MCP?

00:31:46.385 --> 00:31:51.665
On the MCP side, it is just an API standard

00:31:51.665 --> 00:31:53.145
that is tailored for AI agents.

00:31:53.145 --> 00:31:57.185
And it's something that we all know how to do.

00:31:57.185 --> 00:31:58.865
We know how APIs work.

00:31:58.865 --> 00:32:01.825
We know how to make requests and handle responses.

00:32:01.825 --> 00:32:06.065
And as you see with SMCP, the basic part

00:32:06.424 --> 00:32:10.025
of adding a decorator to a function,

00:32:10.025 --> 00:32:14.185
this is not that difficult. In the past,

00:32:14.185 --> 00:32:16.425
I would feel really bad about telling you all,

00:32:16.425 --> 00:32:17.304
this is really easy.

00:32:17.304 --> 00:32:18.224
You should just do it.

00:32:18.224 --> 00:32:21.705
But it's easy for your agents to do.

00:32:21.705 --> 00:32:29.345
And so I'm not trying to imply that there's no skill involved.

00:32:29.345 --> 00:32:33.224
But you can really prompt your way

00:32:33.224 --> 00:32:38.264
to getting a well-functioning MCP server pretty quickly.

00:32:38.264 --> 00:32:39.504
And it's important.

00:32:39.504 --> 00:32:42.624
By being thoughtful about the design of it,

00:32:42.624 --> 00:32:47.544
by building your own, you can limit what is exposed.

00:32:47.544 --> 00:32:49.785
And this is great for getting your agent

00:32:49.785 --> 00:32:53.065
to do the thing you want it to do more efficiently, more

00:32:53.065 --> 00:32:57.904
cheaply, but also to limit your security risks.

00:32:58.904 --> 00:33:05.425
Or not MCP, command line utilities are great.

00:33:05.425 --> 00:33:07.425
And if there's one that you want to use

00:33:07.425 --> 00:33:10.385
that's widely available in the training data,

00:33:10.385 --> 00:33:13.224
and you're in an environment where your agent can call

00:33:13.224 --> 00:33:16.624
Bash and call the tool, great.

00:33:16.624 --> 00:33:17.465
Use it.

00:33:17.465 --> 00:33:22.584
You don't need to use the GitHub MCP if you have GH.

00:33:22.584 --> 00:33:25.185
I've got a number of different agent things

00:33:25.185 --> 00:33:26.424
deployed in different places.

00:33:26.424 --> 00:33:29.465
Some of them explicitly say, use GH.

00:33:29.465 --> 00:33:31.265
Do not try to use GitHub MCP.

00:33:31.265 --> 00:33:33.504
You don't have GitHub MCP.

00:33:33.504 --> 00:33:35.704
And then there's other ones where I've only

00:33:35.704 --> 00:33:39.304
given it MCP tools because I don't want it writing things

00:33:39.304 --> 00:33:40.224
to the file system.

00:33:40.224 --> 00:33:41.424
It's an ephemeral place.

00:33:41.424 --> 00:33:43.064
I haven't done a checkout of any code.

00:33:43.064 --> 00:33:45.784
I don't want it to fetch a GitHub token

00:33:45.784 --> 00:33:47.125
and then go to the command line.

00:33:47.125 --> 00:33:51.064
I want it to use the tools I provided here.

00:33:51.064 --> 00:33:54.344
Depends on the context of what you need.

00:33:54.344 --> 00:33:55.344
Skills are great.

00:33:55.344 --> 00:33:57.905
Not a substitute for MCP or command line utilities,

00:33:57.905 --> 00:33:59.985
but they really go well with them

00:33:59.985 --> 00:34:02.385
when you need to describe what you

00:34:02.385 --> 00:34:05.144
want to do with those tools.

00:34:05.144 --> 00:34:10.025
And local MCP is better than not.

00:34:10.025 --> 00:34:15.304
I think remote has the best properties for security

00:34:15.304 --> 00:34:21.905
and enterprise reliability, but building one

00:34:21.905 --> 00:34:24.825
that you run locally also works.

00:34:24.825 --> 00:34:26.584
So I'm going to stop there.

00:34:26.584 --> 00:34:28.105
There's a link, again, to the repo

00:34:28.105 --> 00:34:30.545
and to these slides if you want to view them.

00:34:30.545 --> 00:34:32.344
Thank you very much.
